A3: SPL Library Checkouts

Introduction

I chose to analyze data on books with subjects that include Self Help in the years 2005-2022. In recent years, mental health conditions have increased world-wide. Many mental health awareness movements have emerged to emphasize the importance of mental health and pushed the topic to the forefront of peoples minds. Coming out of a period with large historic events, such as the 2020 Black Lives Matter protests and the COVID-19 pandemic, there has been tremendous unseen impacts on mental health. I am curious to see if this shift in self-wellness is reflected in Seattle Public Library book checkouts.

Summary Information

In my findings, the average number of checkouts for self help titles is 1285 a month at the Seattle Public Library, with each title getting checked out an average of 3.77 times. The average number of checkouts for self help titles in a year is 15212 a year. There has been a steady increase in the number of checkouts of self help books with the most number of checkouts occurring in 2022 and the least amount of checkouts occurring in 2005. The number checkouts for physical self help books in the Seattle Public Library have increased overtime with a small decline in 2020. I also calculated the most checked out books in each year to see which self help titles were the most popular. The most checked out self help books throughout the years contained a healthy mix of books, video recordings, and eBooks, including titles like Mozart and the whale, The Fault in our Stars, and The Light We Carry: Overcoming in Uncertain Times.

The Dataset

The Seattle government collects data from the Seattle Public Library. The data is collected from 2005 to current day and collected initial checkouts of physical and electronic media like books, eBook, audio books, movies, etc. available at the library. Checkout data comes from multiple current and historical records. For digital items, they get data from media vendors like, Overdrive, hoopla, Freegal, and RBDigital. This data is collected due to an open data initiative to get information on which books are being circulated and what people are reading. Some ethical concerns I have about this data is how it ensures privacy for the individuals checking out. The legal media that you choose to consumer should be at your own discretion. If they can track which books are being checked out, how are the guaranteeing anonymity to the consumer? One limitation to this data is the records available. This data does not go beyond 2005 and its data for the year 2023 is incomplete, for this reason I chose to filter out 2023. Some other problems include the inconsistent publications dates and repeat titles.

First Trends Over Time Chart

This line chart shows the trends of digital and physical self help media being checked out from the Seattle Public Library in 2005-2022. I included this chart because they way in which people are consuming media has become more digital. I wanted to visualize at which rate are physical and digital media being consumed and how it was affected during 2020, when many people could not go to the library to get physical media. I noticed that the plot and line for physical usage class dipped near 2019-2020. On the other hand, digital media has been checked out at an exponential rate, overtaking physical media around 2018.
